<h2>Artifact Description</h2>
<p>This artifact includes Project One and Project Two from CS 305, which focus on analyzing and improving the security of an existing software system. The original artifact involved identifying vulnerabilities within an application, while the enhanced version implemented solutions to address those weaknesses using secure coding practices and modern security tools.
This artifact supports organizational decision-making by identifying risks that could impact system reliability, data integrity, and user trust, and by providing actionable improvements to mitigate those risks.
</p>

<h2>Enhancements Implemented</h2>
<p>The original system contained several critical vulnerabilities, including the lack of HTTPS communication, weak authentication mechanisms, insufficient input validation, and the absence of encryption. To enhance the artifact, I implemented multiple improvements to strengthen system security and reliability. These enhancements included configuring HTTPS using SSL certificates to secure data transmission, applying SHA-256 hashing and AES encryption to protect sensitive data, and improving input validation to prevent injection attacks and invalid data entry. I also updated outdated dependencies and utilized dependency-check tools to identify and address known vulnerabilities.
In addition, I developed a Python-based security module to demonstrate the practical implementation of these improvements. This module incorporates hashing, encryption, and input validation, along with a simulation of secure communication to reflect the transition from HTTP to HTTPS.
</p>

